<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1891-05-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1891-05-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="599" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d599">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Wharton</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Douglass</persName></hi>.</head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1891-05-16"><hi rend="italic">May 16,
                            1891</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 116.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department is gratified to receive your
                        No. 157, of the 27th ultimo, inclosing copies of correspondence, from which
                        it appears that the Haitian Government promises to make an executive measure
                        the proposed law repealing the existing law by which sailing vessels are
                        detained in the ports of Haiti until the duties on their inward cargoes are
                        paid.</p>
                    <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">William F. Wharton</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary</hi>.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>